      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-mrl5-criteria-001",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9) operates under a documented software quality assurance plan conforming to FDA guidance on software as a medical device. Version control, regression testing suite (847 test cases), and change management procedures are in place. SQA audit completed 2024-11 with zero critical findings. Achieved Gradation 3 satisfies the MRL-5 required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-mrl5-criteria-002",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver and the power-law hemolysis transport equation. Observed spatial order of accuracy (1.94) is consistent with the nominal second-order scheme. Temporal convergence confirmed separately. All MMS residuals within machine precision tolerances. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-mrl5-criteria-003",
      "rationale": "Three-mesh GCI study performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry. Refinement ratio r = 1.587 (factor of 4 cell count increase per level). GCI fine = 3.2% for hemolysis index QoI, 2.1% for pressure head. Monotonic convergence confirmed; apparent order p = 1.91. Richardson-extrapolated reference values used in subsequent validation comparisons. Exceeds required Gradation 3; Gradation 4 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5-criteria-004",
      "rationale": "In-vitro hemolysis experiments conducted under controlled temperature (37 ± 0.5 °C), hematocrit (33 ± 1%), and anticoagulation protocol. Flow loop calibration traceable to NIST standards. Five operating points (3–6 L/min, 2400–3600 RPM) bracket the clinical VAD operating envelope. Experimental uncertainty in NIH measurement ± 8% (95% CI) documented. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5-criteria-005",
      "rationale": "Quantitative validation metric (E_rel) computed for NIH at each of the five operating points. Mean |E_rel| = 11.3% (range 6.8–14.9%), all within the ± 15% acceptance band. PIV velocity field comparison shows MAE < 4% of bulk velocity. Statistical hypothesis testing (Wilcoxon signed-rank) confirms no systematic bias (p = 0.31). Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5-criteria-006",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) is the direct clinical endpoint used in regulatory submissions for VAD devices. Secondary QoIs (pressure head, shear stress distribution) are mechanistically linked to hemolysis and validated independently. QoI traceability matrix maps each modeled output to the COU decision need. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl5-criteria-007",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments use the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry as the COU device surrogate. Operating conditions span the full clinical VAD envelope. Blood analog fluid (porcine blood, matched hematocrit) used in experiments. The validation hierarchy explicitly maps bench experiments to the COU prediction context. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-mrl5-criteria-008",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored via residual norms (all < 1×10⁻⁶) and QoI stabilization (NIH variation < 0.1% over final 500 iterations). Round-off error assessed via double-precision arithmetic throughout; negligible compared to discretization error. Solver restarts and parallel decomposition consistency verified. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-mrl5-criteria-009",
      "rationale": "Simulation workflow is documented in a controlled simulation plan reviewed by an independent CFD engineer. Boundary condition setup, mesh generation parameters, and post-processing scripts are version-controlled. Independent replication of one operating point by a second analyst confirmed consistent NIH results (< 1% difference). Gradation 2 achieved, meeting the required level for this factor under MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-mrl5-criteria-010",
      "rationale": "The power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger correlation with Arora modification) is the accepted standard for CFD hemolysis prediction in rotary blood pumps. Model form uncertainty quantified via comparison of three published hemolysis model variants; spread in NIH predictions < 18% across models, consistent with reported literature variability. k-ω SST turbulence model selected based on prior benchmark studies for rotating machinery. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-mrl5-criteria-011",
      "rationale": "All boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, outlet pressure) derived from calibrated experimental measurements with documented uncertainty. Blood rheological parameters (viscosity, density) assigned from literature with population variability characterized. Monte Carlo propagation of input uncertainty (10,000 samples) performed; sensitivity indices (Sobol) identify rotational speed and hemolysis model coefficients as dominant contributors. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-mrl5-criteria-012",
      "rationale": "In-vitro hemolysis experiments conducted on three independently manufactured pump specimens to capture unit-to-unit geometric variability. Each specimen tested in triplicate at each operating point (n = 45 total measurements). Inter-specimen variability in NIH < 9% (CV), within expected manufacturing tolerance effects. Sample size justification documented via power analysis targeting 80% power at 15% effect size. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/equiv-input-mrl5-criteria-013",
      "rationale": "The Equivalency of input parameters factor addresses the degree to which the input parameters used in the validation experiments match those of the clinical use context. For this COU, the validation experiments employ porcine blood at 37 °C and hematocrit 33%, which closely approximates typical VAD patient blood properties. The primary source of non-equivalency would be patient-to-patient variability in blood rheology (viscosity, yield stress, RBC deformability) and the use of porcine rather than human erythrocytes. After deliberation, the assessment team determined that this factor is appropriately scoped out for the following reasons: (1) Sensitivity analysis via Monte Carlo propagation (see Model inputs factor and UQ result VR-004) already explicitly propagates blood viscosity and hematocrit uncertainty through the CFD model, effectively capturing the dominant rheological input variability within the quantified uncertainty bounds; (2) Published literature (Arora et al. 2004; Giersiepen et al. 1990; Taskin et al. 2012) demonstrates that porcine RBC hemolytic susceptibility is within 12% of human RBC susceptibility under equivalent shear-exposure conditions, a difference already encompassed by the ± 15% NIH acceptance band; (3) The operating conditions (flow rate, rotational speed) are directly controlled and matched between validation and COU contexts — the only non-equivalency pertains to biological material properties, not geometric or kinematic parameters; (4) Conducting a separate formal equivalency assessment would require patient-specific blood samples under IRB protocols that are outside the scope of the current regulatory submission timeline, and the marginal reduction in uncertainty does not justify the added burden given that the 95th-percentile Monte Carlo NIH prediction remains 22% below the clinical threshold. The team acknowledges this is a marginal scoping decision at MRL 5 and has documented it as a formal epistemic gap. Future submissions for a modified device should include a dedicated human-blood equivalency study to close this gap."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU2 (VAD hemolysis prediction at MRL 5) is accepted based on the following structured evidence: (1) All 12 assessed credibility factors achieve levels meeting or exceeding their required levels under the MRL-5 credibility goal framework. (2) The single scoped-out factor (Equivalency of input parameters) is supported by a documented, thorough rationale demonstrating that the dominant source of non-equivalency (blood rheology variability) is already captured within the Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification performed under the Model inputs factor, and that the residual uncertainty is bounded within the established acceptance band. (3) Four independent validation results (PIV velocity field, hemolysis index, mesh convergence, and Monte Carlo UQ propagation) collectively demonstrate that the CFD model predicts absolute NIH values within 15% of experimental measurements across all five operating points, with 95th-percentile uncertainty intervals remaining 22% below the clinical hemolysis threshold. (4) The provenance chain from raw experimental data through model predictions to this decision record is complete and traceable. The assessment team judges that the accumulated credibility evidence is sufficient to support regulatory use of the CFD model as the primary basis for hemolysis acceptance for this Class III VAD device.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
